rization2star  aEminent scholar Saikrishna Prakash offers the first truly comprehensive study of the original American presidency. Drawing from a vast range of sources both well known and obscure, this volume reconstructs the powers and duties of the nation's chief executive at the Constitution's founding. Among other subjects, Prakash examines the term and structure of the office of the president, as well as the president's power as constitutional executor of the law, authority in foreign policy, role as commander in chief, level of control during emergencies, and relationship with the Congress, the courts, and the states. This ambitious and even-handed analysis counters numerous misconceptions about the presidency and fairly demonstrates that the office was seen as monarchical from its inception.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aConstitutional historyxUnited States. 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aExecutive powerxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aExecutive powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aJudgesxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aLegislative powerxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aLegislative powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical leadershipxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPresidentsxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aRepublicanismxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aRepublicanismzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97803002